No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today refused to request that, in the context of an amendment to the Criminal Code, the paragraph on which the opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko was convicted be abolished.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned Minister of Expremium, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the request for a reduction in the penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for the conclusion of an allegedly negative contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, and the appeal of the convicted is due to be brought before the court in December.
Timoshenko himself described the verdict as a political revenge of the regime, and in the West, too, the trial raised suspicions of the court's bias.
The motion to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Secretary of State was convicted, from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 Members.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
