Start of a new crisis era
France and the rest of Europe in the focus of investors.
On Tuesday, a statistical storm broke through Europe.
The individual countries published their data on their GDP for the third quarter.
The Czech economy stagnated compared to the previous quarter, Germany and France increased.
But today the bond market is breaking all records.
Investors not only keep an eye on Greece, but also on Spain, France, Austria and other countries.
The statistical offices of the European Zone, Germany, the Czech Republic and some other European countries published their preliminary forecasts of economic developments in the third quarter.
Germany's GDP was expected to grow by 0.5%, France by 0.4%.
At the same time, both countries corrected their data for the second quarter, in which Germany recorded higher growth than originally expected (growth of 0.3% instead of predicted 0.1%), while France admitted a slight decrease of 0.1% (original data only referred to stagnation).
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in this year's third quarter compared to the previous year.
Compared to the previous quarter, however, the gross domestic product stagnated and, according to the Statistical Office, the trend of slowing down economic performance was confirmed.
The results are therefore worse than the analysts' forecasts.
The main events:
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in this year's third quarter compared to the previous year, but it stagnated compared to the previous quarter.
According to provisional and seasonal data, the German economy grew by 0.5 percent in the third quarter.
In the eurozone as a whole and in the EU, the economy recorded growth of 0.2 percent between July and September compared to the previous quarter, which is consistent with the analysts' expectations.
The Greek economy shrank by 5.2 percent compared to the previous year.
The return on their 10-year government bonds climbed to 28,45%.
The return on Italian and Spanish government bonds rose to its critical limits.
Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium and other countries are also beginning to feel problems...
The yield on Czech government bonds is below 4%, although the situation in the region is deteriorating.
In Germany, voices are heard that the ECB should become the creditor of the last instance.
