Brand Story:
The innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If one wanted to search for a suitable word that characterizes IBM's strategy most accurately, then this would probably be the word "long-term".
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution; it is known as a modern enterprise, although a century has passed since it was founded.
The basis for this longevity was already laid by their first boss - visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
Even he argued that countless worldwide problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a little bit.
His slogan "Think!" thus became a trademark for the life of the future giant (and at the same time the title of the company's internal magazine, which began to be published at IBM in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen's thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
"For us from IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for an entire century because it remained faithful to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around.
This allowed us to transform technologies, business and society in the course of our first century.
We hope that we will do even more in the next hundred years," said Samuel J. Palmisano, today's director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Thoughtful system
Watson already in the thirties operated social care of his employees - in a similar way as the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: The IBM people had as one of the first American employees paid holidays, an insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as work clothes and a thoughtful remuneration system for best newer and dealer.
IBM's long-term relationships with its customers are equally sophisticated.
From the beginning, the company was brilliant in promoting talent - as one of the first companies in the world IBM lifted any discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy is also the current plan that Palmisan will be replaced by a woman at the head of IBM next year - Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, and has so far taken on the position of head of sales, marketing and strategy.
IBM has been making so-called online brainstormings in recent years, from which many future strategies and innovations develop.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, almost half a million people are employed in the company.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unwavering position in the business guarantees the company a strong image and this to the inside and to the outside.
"From the beginning IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a technology company," said Economist, Harvard Business School professor and author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technologies," added George Colony of Consulting-Company Forrester Research.
As the company itself points out, it is a difference to be present on the market only or to shape it directly through this presence.
IBM - in the states of its logo called "Big Blue" for family reasons, has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies in the world - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructures, hosting and consultation services in an incredible product width - from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM owns the most patents and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His most well-known inventions include, for example, ATMs, credit cards, financial swaps, barcodes or even the diskette.
IBM was the second largest technology company this year (just after Apple), with a market value of around 220 billion dollars, and it has overtaken Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today's customers - for example, the attempt with its own operating system OS/2, the online service Prodigy or the computers IBM PC jr were unhappy.
"Business is based on forward movement, so one must not emotionally bind oneself to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
Therefore, IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms - and if they do not work, they also leave them again.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, who basically stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising Technologies
One fifth of IBM's profits are accounted for by services, software and hardware.
In 1990 hardware with a more than fifty percent share was still the most represented.
Since 2000, IBM has sold little profit-disposing assets worth $15 billion, but at the same time it invested $58 billion in the purchase of promising technologies.
IBM continues in these investments even after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Here, too, IBM remained faithful to the legacy of its first boss Thomas J. Watson, who increased his investment in the midst of the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that the company IBM survives today's crisis unscathed.
The value of IBM shares has increased by 120 percent since 2008 and the net profit of the company continues to grow.
IBM's corporate slogan is: everything can be changed - only the values cannot be changed.
This is also why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also overcome the next crisis.
IBM story: From cheese cutter to spaceflights
IBM (International Business Machines), founded in New York a hundred years ago, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It was not until 1924 that she took the name IBM - originally it was about a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later IBM company was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous speed card clocks to register the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader then even put the founders of IBM in the shade - Watson's ideas are still based on the company's invincible culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and distribution of all kinds of machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades Watson managed the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped NASA fly into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture in 1964 - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which set the computer standard of that time, came into the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consulting part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business with consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the concept of "smart planet".
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in not even planned areas, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and in city administration.
In the retail sector, IBM recently launched the Smart Commerce platform to help retailers run the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
Already in 1932 IBM founded a branch in the then Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe at all.
Today IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central Office for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, and there is also a top team of world-class researchers working on voice recognition technology.
