Trend in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five approved state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time sold mainly only trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, to the West were only allowed at that time select ones.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the trips to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travels were not possible.
Even then the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to accept huge queues or also stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the thing had not gone by yet.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to obtain the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange commitment.
Thus, the vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend homes and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is the fact that it was impossible to travel to the most popular holiday destination of Czech Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation was lifted to the neighbouring Western European countries, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
For a long time the Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their travels to the West, everyone wanted to have been there at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept in a tent in the park when traveling to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension at the time.
A typical feature of trips abroad from Czechs was a trunk packed with canned food, beer and sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thus also the average salaries increased, which resulted in another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997 travel agencies began to regularly prepare trips by charter flights, making air travel incredibly cheap, thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts, compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, had already had currencyless payments with all the most advanced countries in the world, making travelling even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-official" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was taken - to Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying to far away sunny countries; this year twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 thousand Czechs travel every year to exotic countries!
Another important moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the USA lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) for the first time and for the first time in their history spent more than CZK 15 per person for a single holiday stay, including the cost of the holiday resort.
