Europe’s Most Beautiful Pools
Jump into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pool in UFO-Optik, Punkpools in Budapest: Those who travel through Europe can experience their blue wonder - and after a city tour or a hike, rest their tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where wellness in the water is most beautiful.
If Iris Meder went on a research trip over the past one and a half years, one thing in her luggage was not to be missed: her swimsuit.
Lying back on the water, she looked up in artistically designed domes, swam towards marble dots waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming halls.
If she liked a bath, she took it flying into her notebook - including interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools explored architectural historian Meder in this way - and now presents her in her recently published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historical bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Through 13 countries she led her "journey to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland she visited places in Italy, France, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and each one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn't have much to do with sports, says Meder - it's only in the water that it's different.
Only annoying is that swimming fans have to settle for blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can breathe in the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful bird chirping in the park.
"One day I wondered why swimming pools must always be so ugly," says the Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Spätscher in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all senses are served, says Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, swimming halls can be a real feast for the eyes: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in baths."
"On the one hand it is transparent, but on the other hand it reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format illustrated book "Badefreuden" conveys on 190 pages interesting facts about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oasis - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, it found a nitrate-containing water in a rustic karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath, whose basins are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: while you have an eye on the whole city from the Zurich rooftop bath, you can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which you can observe the hustle and bustle on the ski slope.
The perhaps most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
It steams from three bowls open to the top in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal protrude into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool did the pool collector Meder get the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, in the Árpád bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba it smells so strongly of heating oil, which one hardly believes to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen carbonate-containing medicinal water, which is almost black and whose slick sticks to your skin as soon as you slide into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: When she wanted to visit the free and sunbathing in the Czech bath Luhatschowitz, she found a closed-off terrain.
The bathroom, designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902, has now been closed.
When Meder took a look through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
On the other hand, one has counteracted the decay in a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of the construction of this bath are already behind it; one can discover not only neo-Roman elements that date back to the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since the careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favourite pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it originally comes from the Black Forest.
"It is already an achievement to merge such different architectural styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace, the dive in the thermal pool is obviously only secondary.
