21er Haus in Vienna
The Moved Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy ending: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and decayed.
Now it is reopened as an exhibition house.
When modern post-war architecture is enthused by clear shapes, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of architect Karl Tacker is a fitting and famous example for the 1958 Brüssler World Exhibition.
At that time, Tacker's pavilion received the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
Construction is still considered a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built Austria's pavilion at the next world exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like side building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected, rebuilt and opened in 1962 as a museum of the 20th century after the world exhibition in the Swiss garden at the Wiener Südbahnhof - the "20s house" was called.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls to hang the art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called the "21s House" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, has completed the new start.
Husslein-Arco, art historian with a considerable career, among other things in youth as a figure skater, later with Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, carried out the reconstruction of politicians and conservationists, procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookshop, and an office building had to be built for it.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was then the ideal occupation for the implementation.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at Tacker at the Technical University of Vienna and because the pavilion was an "unfortunately important place" for him, where he had watched the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost its generosity and ease when he moved to Vienna and re-used it.
There were far greater problems with the current reconstruction: The building was "an energy spinner," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass fibre reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered moat of light between house and street provides the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old reddish-brown anti-rust colour tone.
And the cinema is still exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the monument protection office," says Krischanitz and points to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and modifications, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because an urban developmental stroke of luck has occurred: Around the Swiss garden, the completely newly planned "Central Station Quarter", with office and residential buildings, is created.
And another stroke of luck may still occur: The 21er Haus could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighbourly location in the Swiss garden.
