After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
That's easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
"We found that it was not difficult to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers simply have to use the site's advertising tool to precisely define their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of far-right groups all over Europe and then targeted them with add-ups, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking about their educational level, attitude towards violence and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 very right-wing parties in 11 European countries - without even having to leave their office once.
"It's a quite new research method," says Bartlett.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online supporters of right-wing extreme groups are mostly young, male and annoyed about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Ideas factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends such as "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding three content per day on average, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific work with the name of this page in the title by almost 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study people through this page that you normally cannot reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to question people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"They had to inform the party first and they had never allowed them access," says Bartlett.
"On Facebook, it all falls away - you go straight to them."
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno from the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues has found that students who discussed their frenzy on Facebook tend to drink problems significantly more than students who were silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that peer students, such as residential consultants, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
