How to expose a lie
A look at the current headlines shows how worrying and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
The Republican presidential candidate, Herman Cain, is busy mastering the accusations of sexual harassment on the part of several women, both of whom lie to each other.
Penn State's leadership is accused of perjury because reports have been held back that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nikolas Sarkozy told US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
Congressman Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of the violation of campaign funding related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term at the Oval Office.
Stories about cheating at school and college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers have given their students the exam answers so that they were able to stand up to their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
Many of these lies, however, are considered to be an emergency lie.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognising or exposing lies is one that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Scharaden, in which it is the aim to call "Have you!", the unmasking of a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out extensive research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been exposed.
Lies look into your eyes.
They don't stutter, stammer, blush, and twitch.
However, it cannot be concluded from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and to expose.
A trained liar can penetrate to the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the vast and ever-growing area of decovery, and it is clear that decloaking a deception is a modern ability that is easy to learn and helps us to get the right in our complex world, especially when hiring or questioning people or negotiations or administration are part of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appreciating other people, raising their interest and controlling their own emotions, and they intuitively sense how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people, that men are more often "self-oriented" lies than women, whose lies are more "oriented to others" - usually to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly "fat lies").
We also know that when a person has been exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, by observing this person's normal behavior.
It's called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for assessing changes later.
Observe the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone usually sticks his foot all the time, so that they don't blame him unjustly when he tripples his foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that shrill, not as proof of a de-masking.
People who deceive may freeze when they try to remember their story. Perhaps their feet point towards the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relaxation after interview", this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Questioners often falsely signal that an interview is over just to look for this relaxation after the interview.
Also pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson's slipper is famous when he used the past form when he claimed that his killed wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceiving persons can also use a distant language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question in general.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than objective, which often makes the alarm bells shrill.
There is no magic to expose lies, but you can learn skills that allow you to expose them.
Thanks to these skills, everyone can be less likely to be the victim of fraud, both in private and professional life.
