Climate adversity slowed down the economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in Sinaloa’s economic history. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and raised great hopes regarding economic growth, is in government. However, as a result of climatic adversity, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses of millions in agriculture, but also narrowed the boundaries of the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter of the year.This was mainly due to the historic decline in agricultural development of 31.16 percent, which had a restraining effect on other economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Susttable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582 000 hectares of farmland were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed. The main areas affected were the cultivation of vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity up to November has led to a steady rise in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, with 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloa having no employment, representing 4.53 percent of the labour force. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28% and from July to September to 6.19%, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa, 18,969 more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is due to several factors. Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments, the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently witnessing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, the loss of liquidity on the market as a result of the cutbacks in funds from the legislation passed to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are illegally accumulating dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment also has a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased, due on the one hand to entry problems and on the other hand because it is difficult to find work there as well. These people stay here and look for work here, which increases unemployment," he says.
Undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if one takes into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38 percent of those employed in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work come from low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaria del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos up to September, much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADIs
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) over the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to the Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI amounted to 630 597 dollars from January to June, a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period last year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development), for its part, has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
In the wake of the economic crisis, the state government applied for a loan of 3,000,000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy in July at the National Congress. The state congress approved an amount of 200,600,000 pesos, but no positive impact of debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be observed by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of the entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdé's government incapacity apparent.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (National Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico) argued that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really poor this year, hard work is needed to recover the lost terrain this year and we have to make a double effort in 2012. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well-coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowed economy that is not sufficiently in motion to generate an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. That is why we will conclude the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining Call
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexico Entrepreneurship Association) in Sinaloa, declared that the state should be encouraged to become more dynamic productive.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
There's a lot to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that steers the government's efforts in a better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress in the government.
"There are areas where one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
