In his contribution, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the state government should not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration with general rules.
"I also do not believe that if this were done, the independence of the regulatory body would be affected." She also recalled that the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because it manages state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years around the world, and it results in better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased signal quality and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the use of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest that had not only technical aspects, "for they encompass economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "made the action of the whole system necessary, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that placed the Constitution in the hands of the central government."
It recalled that many countries around the world had already implemented the digital switchover, even though they had highly specialised facilities.
It could not be concluded that, by issuing the contested decree, the government intervened in the powers of Congress, because the laws passed by the legislature were complied with," she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballots in Michoacán individually is considered
