The possibility of individual counting of ballot papers is a reality this year in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governor's elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November, the Electoral Office adopted a series of rules to harmonise local regulations with federal reforms in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, his electoral law or his electoral law to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Gazette within the time limits provided for it, arguing that they still had objections to it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional action filed by the local legislature and judged the State Commissioner's vote on the constitutional reforms to be "invalid and illegal", since he did not have the right to "decide or veto it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview about the possibility of individual counting of votes that thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there would now be the possibility that the local electoral authority could count out the ballots in part or in full.
For example, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be counted in part.The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes of the counting and calculation of votes are not in fact available or are not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total counting of the fully completed ballots may take place if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the winner in second place, who is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the candidates mentioned.
The counting of votes may also take place in its entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the electoral packages that have been subjected to a partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is just under 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
