Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the aircraft accident in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake and another seven people were killed.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transport - SCT (Secretariat for Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation of the accident, in which the Secretary of State Francisco Blake Mora and another seven people were killed, indicated that the helicopter with its whole undamaged structure had hit the ground directly without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary for communications and transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wings had contact with trees at a height of 25 metres, with the helicopter losing the fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, so he fulfilled all the requirements for the transport of the personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the machine had run down.
"No parts of the aircraft were found elsewhere in the search, and the impact affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, so it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, it is a priority to get the results as soon as possible, but this could take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, General Director of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico) assured that the helicopter had flown from Estado Mayor Presidencial at cruising speed and the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information strengthens the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of impact."
At a press conference, the head of SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight. This means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at take-off. During the further flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State, some low-hanging clouds were raised.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that due to the clouds the team had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Impact point:
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter match. There may have been no loss of control over the aircraft or a deviation from the flight route before the impact.
Dispersal of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available up to now suggests that the helicopter had bounced from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter with its intact structure had hit the ground.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the plane at the scene of the accident indicate neither fire nor explosion.
The latest results indicate several soil contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is steep and has a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a meticulous search in an area beyond the restricted area at the scene of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, which reinforces the assumption that the unharmed aircraft structure had bounced against the ground.
MSS announces a research protocol to locate the obesity gene
She is leading a research project on the discovery of the obesity gene in children and adolescents, supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institute of Mexico) announced that it is conducting a research project on the discovery of the gene of obesity in children and adolescents, entitled "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Youth", which aims to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, said that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was set up.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports fields of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are carried out every Saturday from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began on the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of México) and continued on the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México) since October 8th.
When the target of 500 to 600 investigators is reached, the study will be continued on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and completed on the one of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents in the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the global Diabetes Day, he said that the goal would be for three thousand children and adolescents between the ages of six and 14 to complete nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and family disease history to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He also stated that on those Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist), their blood pressure was monitored and blood levels such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (attempt to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out on the occasion of the health staff's concern about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in almost six years the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. Obesity also increased dramatically," the specialist of the IMSS stressed.
He claimed that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average Mexican was 65 percent Indian-American, 30 percent European and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) that is taken to us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the subjects would be a comprehensive study of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even investigate the presence of dark skin folds in the neck and inner arm (akanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-stage diabetes.
All information would be kept confidential and sent to the parents in writing by the doctors. Doctors explain to the parents all measurement results and suggest to them changes in the lifestyle that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors that are responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, most of the day to spend in front of the TV and use means of transport, instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, that is, an increased consumption of sugared beverages and carbohydrates (tameles, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high intake of fat and protein as well as the genetics to be analysed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If attention were paid to the signs of the road surface, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes if the rainy season broke out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (town area of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning and assured that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt surface were done appropriately, the number of potholes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Keyholes from a Technical Perspective", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Mr. Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, in order to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low one - the so-called malthens. Together they give the road surface its characteristic viscous behavior.
Tensile behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and at 50°C almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the majority of the streets of Mexico City had a flexible road surface composed of six layers of material, of which the last three included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt made of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on to it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is designed, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they must produce friction.
The weight of this road surface receives and distributes most of the forces, the supporting layer also needs an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes moist, water penetrates into the layer and is difficult to exit, causing all layers of the road surface to soften and, consequently, potholes to appear.
When a pothole is created," he said, "the surface layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. However, the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be relative to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without using high temperatures.
