So was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Lophoscopeist from Cali went into history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November 4, a Lophoskopist of the Investigation Unit of the Procuratorate (CTI) from Cali came in as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia): "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven Lophoscopeists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González was on duty, a Puerto Tejada man who has been working on criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities of Chocó, where he often had to go into the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
During the week of use against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew from Palmira to Cauca by helicopter.
He knew he was supposed to identify two bodies, and there was suspicion that one of them could be the one of the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world. Therefore, he was to take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he reached the location where the body was, he could not identify it because of its physical appearance, for it was not in the slightest similar to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, wore no glasses and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planting trowel and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body with those on the print sheet.
He had seen it right: it was Alfonso Cano.
That same night, this Puerto Tejada-born man was responsible for informing the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was indeed the head of the FARC.
Searching for traces
For a Dactyloscope from the Sijín in Cali, the appreciation given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use against "Cano" was very important.
Many people don't know our work.
Daktyloscopy is an exact science without a rate of error, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopeists not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery and confirm the identity of the persons arrested.
When they are arrested, many offenders present false identification documents or they do not have any.
We'll take their fingerprints and find them in the database.
The researcher told us that in case of a theft he had to rip a piece of wall out of a house, because the thief had supported himself with his hand at this very point when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Wounds are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we could take the imprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had taken part in several thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints can also be used to relieve or burden suspects of murder.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
During the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be suspect, and in fact, a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A Dactyloscopeist from the CTI stated that "the fingerprints with chemical or physical reagents would be taken from the object."
When they appear, a planting trowel or a band is used to take them away.
After that, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil service.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identification papers," said the CTI expert.
He said that not everything was as shown in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, neither is everything that you touch, a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
