On Monday, 14 November, Prime Minister Lucas Papademos announced to Parliament that the 100 days granted to his government by the Union were not enough to complete this task.
"In order to continue efforts to boost the economy, we need support from our European partners as well as a new budget adjustment programme," said the head of government in his first public speech at the opening of the debate on Parliament's vote of confidence on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken at the Euro Summit on 27 October was the "main task" of the new government, as the country's involvement within the euro area was "at stake", as he added.
Accordingly, M. Papademos has planned to reduce the country's government deficit "in order to reduce the 9%" of today's gross domestic product by the end of the year, which was 10.6 % in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
The rights reject the new austerity measures
On Monday, Antonis Samaras, head of the right wing, had given his consent to the measures already approved regarding an attempt to escape from the debt crisis, but had sent forward that his party would not be prepared to make an additional saving.
"We will not vote in favour of new measures," he said at a congress of his New Democracy Party.
He had agreed to reduce budget deficit and debt, as well as to fight waste, but was hostile to any policy that would prevent economic recovery.
Olli Rehn, the EU Commissioner responsible for economic and monetary affairs, who had prevented the IMF and the EU from releasing the necessary EUR 8 billion loan without a written guarantee from all the parties regarding their support for the planned measures, had replied to Antonio Samaras that his word was sufficient and that he would not sign anything under pressure from outside.
Euthanasia and accompanied suicide must be legalised, according to a panel of experts.
The Canadians live in denial of death, according to a report by the Royal Society of Canada
The panel stated that governments, health care institutions and doctors worked together on pain-relieving treatment to provide the best pain-relieving remedies, including beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in a denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians actually engage in talking to their doctor about conditions under which they want to die and make dispositions for this purpose.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts were involved, interlinked in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This body recommends that the government amend the penal law in such a way as to allow accompanied suicide and euthanasia, where this choice is made, and in the case of patients considered to be able to make such a decision.
As a prelude, the experts cite a recently published survey by the independent company EIU, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the globe.
Although Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "medical care in Canada has produced a culture in which people are afraid of cutting the issue of death."
Medical care or not: 77% of Canadians have no access to pain-killing drugs, according to the experts appointed by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the Canadian majority desire to die at home, 68.6% of them die in the hospital.
From the country as a whole, the rate of hospital deaths in Quebec is highest at 86%.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and accompanied suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that are contrary to the position of the federal government, which has already stated that it intends to make no changes to the penal law concerning euthanasia and accompanied suicide.
But according to the experts, who have inspected all those countries whose approach has legalized or decriminalized euthanasia and accompanied suicide, there is no evidence that such decriminalization would lead to abuses in their application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or accompanied suicide by uncompetent or unwilling persons.
On the contrary, there are much more cases of such violations, especially in those countries where euthanasia and associated suicide are not legalised, as Jocelyn Downie, co-signatory of the report, confirmed in a teleconference yesterday.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Even accompanied suicide is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal here," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians Support Euthanasia
Let us remember that according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010, 85% of the Canadians had already expressed themselves in favour of euthanasia, because they believe that at the end of their lives, they allow people to alleviate their sufferings.
And 66% believe that the fact that euthanasia is legalised does not mean that the message is that the lives of elderly or disabled people are of less value.
With regard to those who have already committed an accompanying suicide, 41% of the respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
As regards the maintenance or cessation of treatment in patients, the report's authors say that the situation is less clear.
They also suggest in their list of recommendations that the criminal law should state that the withdrawal of funds for which a valid refusal had been made should not be considered criminal.
The Panel also calls for health professionals to be trained in the task of respecting the withdrawal of funds at the end of life, and to fear this without criminal prosecution.
The Panel stated that governments, health care institutions and doctors worked together on pain-relieving treatment to provide the best pain-relieving remedies, including beyond cancer cases.
Finally, with regard to the means already widely used in the Canadian health care institutions for pain relief or life-end measures, the Panel calls for at least consideration of these, as they were not used to reduce physical pain and to refer to the same procedures as euthanasia.
Reservations of other experts
Some experts in the field of health care have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of the expert report of the Royal Society of Canada.
RA Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described the position of the reporting experts as "extreme" among other things, since this does not limit the euthanasia practice of patients in the final phase.
"This opens the door to a situation in which everyone who is tired of life and older than 18 years is asking another person to help him commit suicide," says RA Deschamps, who yesterday reviewed a summary of the report.
RA Deschamps also stresses that the authors of the report seemed to place individual responsibility over all other values involved in the social fabric of society.
But now, he says, there are "guidelines and obligations in a society".
Margaret Somerville, specialist in health law, has also expressed "a strong resistance" to the conclusions of the report, which she described as a "pro-euthanasia manifesto".
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, doubts in particular the report on the absence of abuses in certain countries where euthanasia and associated suicide are legalised, such as the Netherlands and Oregon.
