Austria
Entry of a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution
On Tuesday, the government of the great Social-Democratic/Christian-Democratic coalition, which is in power in Austria, decided to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the constitution in order to reduce public deficits and also to avoid possible degradation by rating agencies in Austria's top bond (AAA).
It was the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann, who had announced this decision of the outcome of the Council of Ministers, although the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, that is, far above the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debt level of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's ability to pay had not been reduced to AA+ at a stroke, we would have to pay three billion euros in additional interest every year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice Chancellor and Christian Democratic Foreign Minister.
Austria is also calling for the Brussels summit of the euro area Member States on 26 October: the Heads of State or Government had demanded that the reduction of public deficits be included by the end of 2012 as well as a return to the public balance of accounts in the constitution or by adopting an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian government for this purpose is similar to the "German model" since Germany was the first European country to incorporate such a "rule" into the Constitution.
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should be reduced by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and by 2017, the federal state's structural budget deficit should not exceed the 0.35% limit of GDP, whereas the regional states, as well as the municipalities, should have balanced budgets.
The objective is to eliminate budgetary debt under the 60% criterion established by the Maastricht Agreement in the 2020/21 horizon.
