Energy policy:
Facts Should Win Over Dogmen
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or on the basis of emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
The availability and costs of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is pushing ahead with a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, an enormous proportion of the world's population should not have to give up a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to mitigate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climate irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is neither the case in Belgium, which submits its decision to the need to find a substitute source capable of substitution, nor in Switzerland, which only intends to build nuclear power plants of the last generation.
Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
After Fukushima, the United States has decided to add another unit to its park by restarting the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which is aimed at renewable energy sources, is occasionally presented as a model, reality, however, contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, especially on Russia, as a result of the increased use of imported gas, an increase in CO2 emissions from gas and coal-fired power stations.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives cause for reflection.
Denmark, on the one hand, is the European leader in the wind energy table, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, and on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the stability of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
As the energy price in the globalised economy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of industrial stability on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a sharp increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys showed that this is a price that the large majority of French people are not willing to pay, as it shows resistance to the principle of this source of energy.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a large number of specialized small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
If France were to take the decision to withdraw from nuclear power, a large part of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual EUR 6 billion in capital goods and nuclear energy exports would increasingly shrink.
What electrician would commission an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the decline of his producer was preprogrammed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one has to admit that there is no such thing as a devil's work a miracle medium for the production of electricity.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy demonstrate the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent checks in already existing plants such as at the construction site in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the security concept.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, in Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions, without consequences for man and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was caused by reactor construction as well as indefensible human error.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters that caused the death of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn the same lessons from this accident as it did after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach and a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and constructors of nuclear power plants, the EPR is a draft that enables it to withstand such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable to build a nuclear power plant among the electrical engineers, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by giving them free access to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party leaders dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy was criticized from many angles - overloading police, judicial and administrative bodies due to a policy subject to the figures, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had titled itself.
Recently, the harassment directed against foreign students by the authorities had shaped the newsreels, the Minister of the Interior had casually (see Libération of 23 May) announced that France "had no need of talents, masons or waiters from abroad".
But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right, Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including more than 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", on the left, by Michel Rocard, who explained in 1990 that France "could not absorb the entire poverty of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
The fear of the invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided in 2005 from both right and left.
Both camps perceived immigrants as a burden for the economy and French society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity one is willing to admit to immigrants.
In his programme, Francois Hollande confines himself to banalities, which point out that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections, but it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent publication, which summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there exists a broad consensus among the specialists on the positive impact of the flood of immigrants on economic growth, wages and jobs in the immigration countries.
Limiting immigration would depress growth and harm the labour market situation.
Fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to substitute the domestic labour force, especially the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than native wage-earners, since they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors which are unencumbered in terms of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local wage-earners, while the more qualified among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not in line with labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country where there is a lack of anesthesiologists, this complementarity also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market between locals and migrants.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants results in a factor of a long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas and economic growth introduced by immigrants is beneficial (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social security systems, with an average of around 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 will, on average, contribute a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth" in the beginning of his mandate.
However, these said teeth, which should deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, now remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a sensitive asset.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, after their invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, had passed the entire 20th century over the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Francos in Spain, Salazars in Portugal and the Supreme in Greece.
