Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is supposed to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with glamour and Gloria.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level, last Tuesday on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sound and at the gourmet buffet.
The German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, the Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, the French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart Mark Rutte from the Netherlands symbolically turned together the wheel of the valve, which transports the Russian gas to the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline will deliver 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length connecting the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, the equivalent of total French consumption, will be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the eventuality of building a third line sound on your own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic states.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will enable direct gas to be supplied to Germany, while avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: for them it is now becoming more difficult to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most heavily engaged in the debate, was not afraid to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Scottish pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, is at the expense of defusing European energy, as the project has struck a breach between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to implement its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas reserves are running out.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which the large gas contracts are also important from the political and economic point of view.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers in Lubmin regarding gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete sheathing to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at a depth of about 200 metres.
During their construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be avoided.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed for safety reasons," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have refrained from it, as the Swedes were not eager to see a Russian state society permanently settle at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we will close the gas flow in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In case of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
This case, however, is regarded by the designers as very unlikely, since the welds were estimated to be resistant to one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes from a seagoing vessel, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one metre, is inserted into the inside of the pipe and moved through the gas pressure.
After three complete days of transport through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have united their forces to realize this project.
However, management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated here (each with 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each with 9%).
These five companies have formed a group of companies called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the volume of gas is transported," Jens Müller specified.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should amount to EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders have been able to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea at Lubmin on a sandy, pine forested coastal stretch.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other key figures of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Launched about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine now wants to give the letter a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, by candlelight with writing hours spent.
The notebook of Moleskine is easily recognisable, with its black, rectangular cover, its rubber band, the eggshell-colored sides, aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a specialist consultant at the company, is commissioned to market the new product.
The notebook was inspired by a traditional production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton peck that is used, for example, for upholstery covers.
This type of notebook was very popular among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object that was regarded as an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now responsible for brands at Modo Modo.
Success is coming.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to make a picture of the buyers, as the notebook inspires businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its early years, now employs more than 100 employees and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques of city centers and understands how to assert its identity.
"We followed the zeitgeist and his new need for writing, which exists despite the upswing of the e-mails," Maria Sebregondi explained.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the Moleskine company: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour" in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard pattern cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from his success and cultural zeitgeist and was able to diversify his products: bags, schedules, fillers, computer covers... The brand has the full range of articles.
A success that enviously brings to mind: In the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the Investmentfond SG Capital Europe, today's Syntegra Capital, and thus opened a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th Week of Work for the Disabled".
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice the average: 19% compared to 9% of the total population.
Disheartening?
"No, says Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which organises the "Week of Work for the Disabled".
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, there is still an enormous amount of work to be done."
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for disabled unemployed people before they get a job.
Older people are more likely: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them have no Abitur and only 10,000 disabled people are among the 2.3 million students with higher education qualifications.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% for the overall average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter the labour market and that make up the "core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
Remains the unspoken, the attitudes that are certainly but slowly evolving.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre Association for the journal La Cité stated that the managers surveyed had "a weak level of knowledge of the disabled", which was "overrepresented" by "persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disadvantaged".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled workers, which was laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, dating from 2008, point to a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at around 3%," reports Pierre Blanc, General Director of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Proof: The number of "fees paid" establishments has decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, created strong pressure on the companies," said Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also expresses a real realization, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the establishments employ disabled workers between 20 and 49 employees, while enterprises with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
